{{Other uses|Level Up (disambiguation){{!}}Level Up}} {{Infobox dot-com company | name = LevelUp | company_slogan = | parent = [[Grubhub|Grubhub Inc.]] | logo = Levelup logo.png | logo_size = 320px | caption = | company_type = [[Private company|Private]] | foundation = | founder = [[Seth Priebatsch]] | area_served = [[World]]wide | location_city = [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]] | location_country = [[United States]] | key_people = | revenue = | homepage = [https://www.thelevelup.com/ TheLevelUp.com] | screenshot = | num_employees = 200 | url = {{url|https://www.thelevelup.com}} | registration = Required | launch_date = March 2011 | current_status = Active | language = English | advertising = | alexa = | website_type = [[Mobile Payments]], [[Online food ordering]], [[Order Ahead]] }}
'''LevelUp''' is an American [[mobile ordering]] and [[mobile payments]] platform created by [[Boston, Massachusetts]]-based start-up [[SCVNGR]].<ref name="Wong 2012"/> The LevelUp platform connects restaurants and guests with a customer experience that blends analytics, loyalty, and rewards. LevelUp brings its technology to market in multiple ways: embedded into partner restaurant apps to provide a full-stack customer engagement solution; via an open developer platform powering over 200 mobile apps; and through LevelUp's partner distribution channels, which lets consumers order ahead and avoid the line at restaurants using the apps already on their [[iPhone]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] phones. On July 25, 2018, it was announced that LevelUp would be acquired for US$390 million by [[Grubhub]], an online food delivery platform<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/07/25/grubhub-acquires-levelup/|title=Grubhub acquires payments and loyalty company LevelUp for $390M|work=TechCrunch|access-date=2018-07-25|language=en-US}}</ref>.
==History==
LevelUp was initially launched in March 2011<ref name="Kirsner 2011">{{cite web | last=Kirsner | first=Scott | title=Test-driving SCVNGR's new LevelUp app for local discounts | website=[[Boston Globe]] | date=March 11, 2011 | url=http://archive.boston.com/business/technology/innoeco/2011/03/test-driving_scvngrs_new_level.html | accessdate=June 14, 2016}}</ref> and operated for its first 3 months as a [[Deal of the Day (ecommerce)|daily deals]] platform.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mashable.com/2011/03/10/scvngr-levelup/ |title=SCVNGR Pilots New Hybrid Mobile App for Local Merchant Deals With Game Mechanics|author=Jennifer Van Grove |date=10 March 2011 |publisher=[[Mashable]]}}</ref> In July 2011, LevelUp shifted away from the daily deal space to focus exclusively on their mobile payments solution.<ref name="Sutter 2011">{{cite web |url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/10/12/tech/innovation/levelup-new-york-launch/ |title=LevelUp app aims to keep coupon users coming back|author=Sutter, John D. |date=12 October 2011 |publisher=[[CNN]] }}</ref> In July 2013, around 200,000 users and 3,000 companies were using LevelUp.<ref name="Chen 2012">{{cite web | last=Chen | first=Brian X. | title=LevelUp Tries Dropping the Transaction Fee for Mobile Payments | website=[[The New York Times]] | date=July 12, 2012 | url=http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/07/12/levelup-zero-scvngr/ | accessdate=June 14, 2016}}</ref> In October 2014, around 14,000 stores were using LevelUp.<ref name="Shontell 2014">{{cite web | last=Shontell | first=Alyson | title=Payment Startup LevelUp Thinks It Has Found A Way To Charge Merchants A 0% Credit Card Processing Fee | website=[[Business Insider]] | date=April 16, 2014 | url=http://www.businessinsider.com/levelups-cheap-credit-card-processing-fee-heading-towards-0-2014-4 | accessdate=June 14, 2016}}</ref> In May 2017 they announced that they had raised $50 million in funding, with over 50,000 locations and more than 200 brands using Levelup.<ref name="Ainger 2017">{{cite web | last=Ainger | first=Neil | title=LevelUp mobile app gets $50 million in latest fintech fundraising round | website=[[CNBC]] | date = May 16, 2017 | url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/05/16/levelup-mobile-app-gets-50-million-in-latest-fintech-fundraising-round.html | accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref>
==Overview== The LevelUp mobile application for [[iPhone]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[Windows Phone]] allows registered users to securely link their debit or credit card to a unique QR code displayed within the app. To pay with LevelUp, users scan the QR code on their phone at LevelUp terminals located at local businesses who accept LevelUp as a form of payment.<ref name="Wong 2012"/>
Some merchants that accept LevelUp as a form of payment also offer monetary savings to users.<ref name="Martinez 2011">{{cite web | last=Martinez | first=Edecio | title=LevelUp challenges Groupon's model with trio of deals | website=[[CBS News]] | date=August 29, 2011 | url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/levelup-challenges-groupons-model-with-trio-of-deals/ | accessdate=June 14, 2016}}</ref> Users are given “First-Time Visit Specials” the first time they make a transaction at the merchant's location. Users can also unlock "credit" to a merchant’s store after spending a certain amount at the merchant’s location.<ref name="Sutter 2011"/>
As of June 2016, LevelUp is available for businesses in the Boston,<ref name="Kirsner 2011"/> Chicago,<ref name="Wong 2012">{{cite web | last=Wong | first=Wailin | title=Loyalty program LevelUp to launch in Chicago | date=February 16, 2012 | publisher=''[[Chicago Tribune]]''|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-02-16/business/chi-loyalty-program-levelup-to-launch-in-chicago-20120216_1_loyalty-program-mobile-payments-lightbank | accessdate=June 14, 2016}}</ref> Washington DC, Northern Virginia, Philadelphia,<ref name="Sutter 2011"/> St. Louis, New York City,<ref name="Sutter 2011"/> Atlanta, San Francisco,<ref name="Sutter 2011"/> Dallas, San Diego, Minneapolis, Montgomery, Kansas City, Seattle and Wilmington, NC areas.
In early 2018, the company announced the release of Broadcast, enabling restaurant brands to reach millions of new customers by allowing them to browse live menus, order ahead and pay directly from high traffic apps such as [[Facebook]], [[Facebook Messenger|Messenger]], [[Yelp]], [[Foursquare]], [[Amazon Alexa]] and [[Chase Pay]].
