{{notability|date=March 2018}} {{Infobox Internet exchange point | name = NAP of the Americas | image = [[File:Miami - NAP of the Americas.jpg|270px|NAP of the Americas]] | full_name = NAP of the Americas | abbreviation = NOTA | founded = 2001 | location = {{USA}}, [[Miami]] | members = | ports = | website = [http://www.equinix.com/locations/united-states-colocation/miami-data-centers/ Equinix Miami Data Centers] | peak = | peak_in = | peak_out = | daily = | daily_in = | daily_out = }}
'''Network Access Point''' ('''NAP''') '''of the Americas''' (also called MI1)<ref name="equinix.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.equinix.com/locations/united-states-colocation/miami-data-centers/|title=Miami Data Centers - Internet Exchange Point & Colocation Services by Equinix|author=|date=|website=www.equinix.com|accessdate=19 April 2018}}</ref> is a massive, six-story, 750,000 square foot [[data center]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.datacenterknowledge.com/archives/2009/05/12/a-look-inside-the-nap-of-the-americas/|title=A Look Inside the NAP of the Americas|date=May 12, 2009|author=Rich Miller|publisher=Data Center Knowledge|accessdate=2010-08-20}}</ref> and [[Internet exchange point]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.euro-ix.net/resources/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080519153115/http://www.euro-ix.net/resources/|dead-url=yes|archive-date=2008-05-19|title=Euro-IX public resources|accessdate=}}</ref> in [[Miami, Florida]], operated by [[Equinix]].
The facility is home to 160 network carriers<ref>https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-21178983</ref> and is a pathway for data traffic from the Caribbean and South and Central America to more than 148 countries.<ref name="equinix.com"/>
The NAP of the Americas is built 32 feet above sea level and is designed to withstand [[Saffir–Simpson scale#Category 5|Category 5]] [[hurricane]]-level winds.<ref name="equinix.com"/> It serves as a relay for the [[U.S. Department of State]]'s [[Diplomatic Telecommunications Service]].<ref>{{cite book |title=U.S. Department of State Foreign Affairs Manual Volume 5 Handbook 2: Telecommunications Handbook |publisher=[[U.S. Department of State]] |date=June 6, 2012 |chapter=5-FAH 2 H-510: DTS Network |chapterurl=https://fam.state.gov/FAM/05FAH02/05FAH020510.html |accessdate=December 13, 2015}}</ref>
